[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] In computational geometry, a **bitonic tour** of a set of point sites in the Euclidean plane is a closed polygonal chain that has each site as one of its vertices, such that any vertical line crosses the chain at most twice.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] The **optimal bitonic tour** is a bitonic tour of minimum total length.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] It is a standard exercise in dynamic programming to devise a polynomial time algorithm that constructs the optimal bitonic tour.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] Although the usual method for solving it in this way takes time $O(n^{2})$ , a faster algorithm with time $O(n\log ^{2}n)$ is known.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] The problem of constructing optimal bitonic tours is often credited to Jon L.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] Bentley, who published in 1990 an experimental comparison of many heuristics for the traveling salesman problem; however, Bentley's experiments do not include bitonic tours.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] The first publication that describes the bitonic tour problem appears to be a different 1990 publication, the first edition of the textbook *Introduction to Algorithms* by Thomas H.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] Leiserson, and Ron Rivest, which lists Bentley as the originator of the problem.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] The optimal bitonic tour has no self-crossings, because any two edges that cross can be replaced by an uncrossed pair of edges with shorter total length due to the triangle inequality.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] Therefore, it forms a polygonalization of the input.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] When compared to other tours that might not be bitonic, the optimal bitonic tour is the one that minimizes the total amount of horizontal motion, with ties broken by Euclidean distance.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] For points in the plane with distinct integer x -coordinates and with real-number y -coordinates that lie within an interval of length $2{\sqrt {2}}$ or less, the optimal bitonic tour is an optimal traveling salesperson tour.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] The same dynamic programming algorithm that finds the optimal bitonic tour may be used to solve other variants of the traveling salesman problem that minimize lexicographic combinations of motion in a fixed number of coordinate directions.
[src:held-karp-exact/bitonic-tour] As with the optimal bitonic tour, this problem may be solved by dynamic programming.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] It is an algorithm design paradigm for discrete and combinatorial optimization problems, as well as mathematical optimization.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] A branch-and-bound algorithm consists of a systematic enumeration of candidate solutions by means of state-space search: the set of candidate solutions is thought of as forming a rooted tree with the full set at the root.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The algorithm explores *branches* of this tree, which represent subsets of the solution set.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Before enumerating the candidate solutions of a branch, the branch is checked against upper and lower estimated *bounds* on the optimal solution, and is discarded if it cannot produce a better solution than the best one found so far by the algorithm.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The algorithm depends on efficient estimation of the lower and upper bounds of regions/branches of the search space.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] If no bounds are available, then the algorithm degenerates to an exhaustive search.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The method was first proposed by Ailsa Land and Alison Doig whilst carrying out research at the London School of Economics sponsored by British Petroleum in 1960 for discrete programming, and has become the most commonly used tool for solving NP-hard optimization problems.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The name "branch and bound" first occurred in the work of Little *et al.* on the traveling salesman problem.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The goal of a branch-and-bound algorithm is to find a value x that maximizes or minimizes the value of a real-valued function *f*(*x*), called an objective function, among some set S of admissible or candidate solutions.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The set S is called the search space, or feasible region.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The rest of this section assumes that minimization of *f*(*x*) is desired; this assumption comes without loss of generality, since one can find the maximum value of *f*(*x*) by finding the minimum of *g*(*x*) = −*f*(*x*).
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Turning these principles into a concrete algorithm for a specific optimization problem requires some kind of data structure that represents sets of candidate solutions.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Such a representation is called an *instance* of the problem.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Denote the set of candidate solutions of an instance I by SI.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Using these operations, a B&B algorithm performs a top-down recursive search through the tree of instances formed by the branch operation.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Upon visiting an instance I, it checks whether bound(*I*) is equal to or greater than the current upper bound; if so, I may be safely discarded from the search and the recursion stops.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] This pruning step is usually implemented by maintaining a global variable that records the minimum upper bound seen among all instances examined so far.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The following is the skeleton of a generic branch-and-bound algorithm for minimizing an arbitrary objective function f.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] To obtain an actual algorithm from this, one requires a bounding function bound, that computes lower bounds of f on nodes of the search tree, as well as a problem-specific branching rule.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] As such, the generic algorithm presented here is a higher-order function.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Initialize a queue to hold a partial solution with none of the variables of the problem assigned.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] If N represents a single candidate solution x and *f*(*x*) < *B*, then x is the best solution so far.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Else, *branch* on N to produce new nodes Ni.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Several different queue data structures can be used.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] This FIFO-queue-based implementation yields a breadth-first search.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] A stack (LIFO queue) will yield a depth-first algorithm.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] A best-first branch-and-bound algorithm can be obtained by using a priority queue that sorts nodes on their lower bounds.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] Examples of best-first search algorithms with this premise are Dijkstra's algorithm and its descendant A* search.
[src:held-karp-exact/branch-and-bound] The depth-first variant is recommended when no good heuristic is available for producing an initial solution, because it quickly produces full solutions, and therefore upper bounds.
